## Summary

Extended bringup session. A lot of dead ends, one major direction change, and a clearer path forward than we started with.

---

## What we tried

### Squashfs approach

The KNULLI initramfs mounts a squashfs from `/boot/boot/batocera` inside a FAT32 partition on mmcblk0p3. We replaced that squashfs with our Buildroot rootfs, packaged as a squashfs. The device booted, the initramfs ran, overlayfs mounted. But we couldn't get SSH working and had no way to see what was happening without serial console access.

Attempts to debug:

- Tried adding WiFi init scripts to the squashfs overlay. WiFi occasionally connected (got a ping response once) but SSH never came up.
- Tried adding dropbear with `-R -B` flags. Still not reachable.
- Ordered and received a mini HDMI adapter. KNULLI doesn't enable HDMI output by default and neither does our image, so this didn't help.
- Tried ADB via the KNULLI ADB daemon. Got it working on KNULLI but couldn't replicate on our image without adbd in the rootfs.
- Ordered a TP-Link UE300C USB-C ethernet adapter (RTL8153). The r8152 module is not in the KNULLI kernel modules we extracted, so the adapter doesn't come up.

The fundamental problem throughout: no serial console, no display output, no reliable network. Debugging completely blind.

### Build script

Wrote a proper build script at `tools/build-paw-image.sh` that automates the full image assembly:

- Creates a blank image file
- Writes bootloader blobs at raw offsets
- Creates GPT partition table
- Formats FAT32 boot partition
- Builds squashfs from Buildroot rootfs plus overlay
- Populates FAT32 with squashfs and boot metadata

The overlay system at `feral-os/overlays/paw/` lets us add init scripts and config files without modifying the Buildroot config. This is the right pattern and will carry forward.

